4ï¸âƒ£ What you really learned: â€œvulnerabilities exist due to poor coding practicesâ€

This is the most important realization from Day 13.

Letâ€™s break it down.

5ï¸âƒ£ Example 1: SQL Injection (SQLi)
What happens in DVWA

The application:

Takes user input (username, ID, etc.)

Directly inserts it into a database query

Poor coding practice

No input validation

No parameterized queries

Trusting user input blindly

Why itâ€™s vulnerable

User input becomes part of the SQL command, not just data.

What this teaches you

Databases do exactly what they are told

The vulnerability is not the database

The vulnerability is developer trust in user input

Real-world impact

Login bypass

Data leakage (users, passwords, financial data)

Full database compromise

6ï¸âƒ£ Example 2: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)
What happens in DVWA

The application:

Accepts user input

Displays it back on a webpage

Does not sanitize or encode it

Poor coding practice

No output encoding

No input sanitization

Directly echoing user input

Why itâ€™s vulnerable

Browsers trust server responses.
If the server sends malicious scripts, the browser runs them.

What this teaches you

XSS is about trust boundaries

The browser trusts the website

The website mistakenly trusts the user

Real-world impact

Session hijacking

Cookie theft

Phishing attacks

Account takeover

7ï¸âƒ£ Example 3: Command Injection
What happens in DVWA

The app:

Passes user input to system commands

Executes them on the server

Poor coding practice

No input filtering

Direct OS command execution

No command allowlisting

Why itâ€™s vulnerable

User input becomes part of a system-level command.

What this teaches you

Applications often bridge user input â†’ OS

Any bridge without validation is dangerous

Server-side vulnerabilities are extremely powerful

Real-world impact

Server takeover

Data destruction

Malware installation

8ï¸âƒ£ Authentication flaws you observed

DVWA helps you understand:

Weak passwords

Poor session management

No rate limiting

Predictable tokens

Poor coding practices here

Hardcoded credentials

Weak hashing

No brute-force protection

Key lesson

Authentication vulnerabilities are often:

Simple logic errors

Missing security checks

Not â€œadvanced hackingâ€

9ï¸âƒ£ The BIG lesson DVWA teaches (very important)
Vulnerabilities are not:

âŒ Random
âŒ Advanced tricks
